(234, 1, '2014-06-14 17:13:38', '2014-06-14 17:13:38', '<a href="http://localhost/farming/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/riparian-area.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-227 aligncenter" src="http://localhost/farming/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/riparian-area-300x109.jpg" alt="riparian-area" width="300" height="109" /></a>\r\n\r\nRiparian zones refer to the area that is next to water. The vegetation in healthy riparian zones plays an important role in maintaining the water quality. This provides many benefits for biodiversity (terrestrial species and neighbouring aquatic species), but there are, however, benefits for humans as well:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Improved water quality</strong> for recreational purposes, drinking water in wells and for livestock.</li>\r\n	<li><strong> Water absorption and storage</strong> – maintains water levels in wells, and prevents flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Flood control</strong> — plants on the banks reduce the speed of moving water during storm events, resulting in decreased severity of flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Protecting streambanks</strong> — prevents eroded soil from entering water</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shade</strong> — helps to reduce water temperature, and increase habitat for species such as salmon, which are of interest to anglers.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Carbon sequestration</strong> — plants act as a carbon sink</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shelterbelt</strong> — shrubs and trees act as a windbreak, reducing wind damage</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Riparian Area', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '184-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-14 17:13:38', '2014-06-14 17:13:38', '', 184, 'http://localhost/farming/?p=234', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(235, 1, '2014-06-14 17:14:11', '2014-06-14 17:14:11', '<a href="http://localhost/farming/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/riparian-area.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-227" src="http://localhost/farming/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/riparian-area-300x109.jpg" alt="riparian-area" width="1000" height="365" /></a>\r\n\r\nRiparian zones refer to the area that is next to water. The vegetation in healthy riparian zones plays an important role in maintaining the water quality. This provides many benefits for biodiversity (terrestrial species and neighbouring aquatic species), but there are, however, benefits for humans as well:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Improved water quality</strong> for recreational purposes, drinking water in wells and for livestock.</li>\r\n	<li><strong> Water absorption and storage</strong> – maintains water levels in wells, and prevents flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Flood control</strong> — plants on the banks reduce the speed of moving water during storm events, resulting in decreased severity of flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Protecting streambanks</strong> — prevents eroded soil from entering water</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shade</strong> — helps to reduce water temperature, and increase habitat for species such as salmon, which are of interest to anglers.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Carbon sequestration</strong> — plants act as a carbon sink</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shelterbelt</strong> — shrubs and trees act as a windbreak, reducing wind damage</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Riparian Area', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '184-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-14 17:14:11', '2014-06-14 17:14:11', '', 184, 'http://localhost/farming/?p=235', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(240, 1, '2014-06-16 18:49:39', '2014-06-16 18:49:39', '<i><b>Planting Vegetated Buffers/Grassy Headlands</b></i>\r\n\r\nTo prevent erosion and promote water filtration vegetation should be present along riparian areas. In some places it may not be possible to keep woody vegetation such as trees or bushes, for example the borders of field crops adjacent to waterways. Grassy strips or headlands are intended for filtration and a setback is an area of land that is left “untouched”. Together these areas are called “Vegetated Buffers”. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer.\r\n\r\nKeeping soil covered by some grass will have multiple benefits for both biodiversity and the farm. Grass will help to reduce erosion as the root mass help to maintain the soil. Helping soil biodiversity will help to improve soil quality through the preservation of soil nutrients and soil structure. Grasses will also act as a filter, helping to reduce the amount of loose soil or suspended inputs such as pesticides or fertilizers washed into neighbouring waterways.\r\n\r\n<b>Grassy strips</b> or headlands are intended for filtration and a <b>setback</b> is an area of land that is left “untouched”. Together these areas form “Vegetated Buffers”. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer. For more information about both setbacks and grassy strips can be found below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Setbacks & Buffers', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'setbacks-buffers', '', '', '2014-06-17 14:01:39', '2014-06-17 14:01:39', '', 184, 'http://localhost/farming/?page_id=240', 0, 'page', '', 0),
