(258, 1, '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '<i><b>Planting Vegetated Buffers/Grassy Headlands</b></i>\r\n\r\nTo prevent erosion and promote water filtration vegetation should be present along riparian areas. In some places it may not be possible to keep woody vegetation such as trees or bushes, for example the borders of field crops adjacent to waterways. Grassy strips or headlands are intended for filtration and a setback is an area of land that is left “untouched”. Together these areas are called “Vegetated Buffers”. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer.\r\n\r\nKeeping soil covered by some grass will have multiple benefits for both biodiversity and the farm. Grass will help to reduce erosion as the root mass help to maintain the soil. Helping soil biodiversity will help to improve soil quality through the preservation of soil nutrients and soil structure. Grasses will also act as a filter, helping to reduce the amount of loose soil or suspended inputs such as pesticides or fertilizers washed into neighbouring waterways.\r\n\r\n<b>Grassy strips</b> or headlands are intended for filtration and a <b>setback</b> is an area of land that is left “untouched”. Together these areas form “Vegetated Buffers”. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer. For more information about both setbacks and grassy strips can be found below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Setbacks & Buffers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '240-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '', 240, 'http://localhost/farming/?p=258', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(259, 1, '2014-06-17 13:58:04', '2014-06-17 13:58:04', 'Grass should be present along crop edges, especially those bordering watercourses. For the maximum amount filtration to occur, the plants must be dense and established—15 to 20cm (6-8 inches) sod-forming vegetation that uniformly covers at least 90% of a square-meter plot. Grass species can be sown, but you can also allow the plants to establish themselves. However, there may be a risk of weed influx if this is done in a crop.\r\n\r\nThe width of a vegetated buffer is measured from the crop to the water source (measured from the sediment bed, usually the edge of the water). It is recommended that vegetated buffers (including grassy headlands/strips) should be about 5-10 meters in width for water filtration to occur. However this width is dependent on the crop (potatoes for example require a larger width compared to less intensive crops such as corn) as well as how steep the land is—steeper land requires more coverage as rainwater may form gullies and rivulets. More information about buffer width can be found in the <a href="http://localhost/farming/?page_id=263"><strong>Setback section</strong><span style="color: #ff0000;">.</span></a>', 'Grassy Strips & Buffers', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'grassy-strips-buffers', '', '', '2014-06-17 14:07:39', '2014-06-17 14:07:39', '', 240, 'http://localhost/farming/?page_id=259', 0, 'page', '', 0),
